{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539441"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:41:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:41:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16595"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16595"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.75,0.03,0.06,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9286"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9286"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51280"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3168"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21994"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by police after being found wandering in traffic. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His parent reports he has become increasingly withdrawn over the past six months and has stopped attending university.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears dishevelled with poor eye contact. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. During the mental state examination, he becomes agitated and states \u0027The zoop-masters are controlling my brain-waves with their mindification rays. They splorkify my thoughts every night.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s speech pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Echolalia","Neologism","Circumstantiality","Tangentiality","Word salad"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient demonstrates features suggestive of psychosis, including paranoid delusions and disorganised speech. The most striking feature of his speech is the creation of new words (\u0027zoop-masters\u0027, \u0027mindification\u0027, \u0027splorkify\u0027) that have no meaning to anyone except the patient. These are examples of \u003Cstrong\u003Eneologisms\u003C/strong\u003E, which are newly created words or phrases that often combine existing words or word parts in novel ways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECircumstantiality\u003C/strong\u003E refers to speech that is indirect and delayed in reaching its goal, but eventually arrives at the intended point. While providing excessive detail, the train of thought is maintained. This pattern is not demonstrated in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcholalia\u003C/strong\u003E is the meaningless repetition of words or phrases spoken by others. This pattern is not demonstrated in the stem, as the patient is creating new words rather than repeating existing ones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETangentiality\u003C/strong\u003E refers to speech that moves from topic to topic in an unrelated manner and never returns to the original point. While the patient\u0027s speech is disordered, the primary feature is the creation of new words rather than moving between unrelated topics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWord salad\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a pattern of speech that is incoherent and disorganised, with words and phrases combined in a meaningless way. While there is some disorganisation in the patient\u0027s speech, the primary feature is the creation of new words rather than the meaningless combination of existing words.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeologisms are considered a feature of formal thought disorder and are commonly associated with schizophrenia. Their presence, along with other symptoms such as social withdrawal, paranoid delusions, and disorganised speech, suggests a possible first episode of psychosis requiring urgent psychiatric assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neologisms are newly created words or phrases that have meaning only to the patient, and are a feature of thought disorder in psychosis.","The presence of neologisms suggests formal thought disorder and is commonly associated with schizophrenia.","Assessment of thought form includes evaluation for neologisms, tangentiality, circumstantiality, and thought blocking."],"references":["Sadock BJ, Sadock VA, Ruiz P. Kaplan and Sadock\u0027s comprehensive textbook of psychiatry. lippincott Williams \u0026 wilkins; 2017 May 11."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51280"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16595"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51280"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T09:09:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T09:09:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9286"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65835"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/188"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Psychotic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T14:32:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/225"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Schizophrenia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-20T19:32:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups